In Week 9, the story of Trump\'92s second term turned more openly on who counts as part of the political community and who does not. The week\'92s events revealed a government that no longer hides its preference for some lives over others, or its impatience with limits on its will. Migrants, students, disabled people, and dissenting institutions all felt the weight of a state that now treats law as a tool to be aimed, not a boundary to be honored. At the same time, courts, state officials, and civil society tried to hold the line, but they did so against a rising tide of executive orders, agency purges, and public attacks on judges. The pattern was not a single dramatic break. It was a dense layering of actions that, taken together, narrowed the space in which democracy can breathe.\
\
At the start of Week 9, the Democracy Clock stood at 8:43 p.m. By the end, it had moved to 8:48 p.m., a shift of 5.4 minutes toward midnight. That movement reflects more than the volume of events; it marks a change in how power is used. The administration not only invoked an eighteenth\uc0\u8209 century wartime law to deport migrants, it continued flights after a federal judge ordered them halted, then called for that judge\'92s impeachment when he insisted on his authority. It did not only threaten universities with investigations; it clawed back hundreds of millions of dollars and tied the return of funds to demands that campuses suppress protest and reshape their curricula. It did not only criticize the press; it dismantled the government\'92s own international broadcasting system and barred a major wire service from the Oval Office. In each domain, the same lesson was taught: oversight can be ignored, opposition can be punished, and citizenship can be graded by origin, loyalty, and usefulness to those in power.\
\
The most direct expression of this new order came through the use of the Alien Enemies Act and related deportation tools. President Trump formally invoked the 1798 statute to expel alleged members of the Venezuelan gang Tren de Aragua, even though the United States is not at war with Venezuela. Under that banner, the administration deported more than 200 men to El Salvador, paying that government to confine them in a maximum\uc0\u8209 security prison. Tattoos and rumor often stood in for evidence. A Venezuelan makeup artist and LGBTQ+ asylum seeker was sent to a Salvadoran prison on the strength of religious crown tattoos that U.S. officials read as gang symbols. A Brown University medical professor was deported to Lebanon despite a judge\'92s order requiring 48 hours\'92 notice before removal. A sworn ICE declaration later admitted that many deportees had no criminal records at all. Law here did not function as a shield. It was the weapon itself.\
\
When federal judges tried to draw a line, the executive branch stepped over it. Judge James Boasberg issued a temporary restraining order blocking deportations under the Alien Enemies Act and, in a separate order, directed that planes already in the air be turned back. The administration let the flights land in El Salvador anyway, then argued that the judge\'92s authority ended once the planes left U.S. airspace and that his verbal instructions did not bind them because they were not yet written. Other courts halted deportations of specific individuals, such as Mahmoud Khalil, a Palestinian activist and permanent resident, and Badar Khan Suri, an Indian academic at Georgetown, but those rulings came against a backdrop of mass removals already carried out. The message from the executive was blunt: court orders were treated as suggestions, to be parsed and evaded rather than obeyed.\
\
The confrontation did not stop at disobedience. President Trump publicly labeled Judge Boasberg a \'93radical left lunatic\'94 and called for his impeachment after the restraining order. A Republican congressman from Texas followed with formal articles of impeachment, turning a constitutional remedy for grave misconduct into a partisan response to an unwelcome ruling. The Department of Justice asked an appeals court to remove Boasberg from the case altogether, arguing that his orders exceeded his power. The White House press secretary misrepresented his decisions from the podium and attacked his wife\'92s political donations. Outside the courthouse, MAGA supporters issued bomb threats against judges, including a conservative Supreme Court justice who had ruled against administration positions. Chief Justice John Roberts issued an unusual public rebuke, reminding the country that impeachment is not a tool for policy disagreement. His words mattered, but they did not erase the fact that the executive had now normalized open hostility to judicial independence.\
\
While courts struggled to hold their ground, the administration moved quickly to reshape the civil service and the machinery of government itself. The Department of Government Efficiency, or DOGE, continued to act as the spearpoint of this effort. Its teams had already helped shutter USAID; this week, a federal judge ruled that dismantling the aid agency likely violated the Constitution and ordered parts of it restored. DOGE workers forced their way into the U.S. Institute of Peace building, despite the institution\'92s claim to independent status, and the administration removed the institute\'92s board in what its former CEO called an illegal takeover. DOGE operatives also arrived at the Institute of Museum and Library Services, sent staff home, swore in a new acting director, and canceled contracts and grants, following an executive order to eliminate the agency. These moves did not merely trim budgets. They stripped Congress\uc0\u8209 created institutions of their autonomy and repurposed their assets under direct executive control.\
\
At the same time, DOGE sought sweeping access to federal data systems. President Trump signed an order granting the office broad rights to unclassified agency records, software, and data, framed as a way to eliminate \'93information silos\'94 and root out waste. DOGE then turned to the Social Security Administration, attempting to mine its systems for evidence of fraud. Two federal judges, in separate cases, blocked DOGE from accessing Social Security data, calling its efforts a \'93fishing expedition\'94 and ordering the destruction of any personal information already obtained. Yet the underlying pattern remained. A politically led office, closely tied to a single billionaire adviser, was being positioned as a central node through which information about citizens and agencies would flow, with courts forced to intervene after the fact to protect privacy and legality.\
