The week also saw the deepening of a particular relationship between the state and a small circle of private actors, most notably Elon Musk. Starlink internet service was installed across the White House campus as a \'93donation,\'94 carried out by a Musk employee who also worked for DOGE. The installation was not properly coordinated with the Secret Service, triggered a security alert, and raised questions about procurement rules and conflicts of interest. The Federal Aviation Administration canceled a $2.4 billion contract with Verizon and instead paid Starlink to manage U.S. airspace, prompting Democratic senators to call for investigations into possible corruption. Musk was scheduled to receive a Pentagon briefing on U.S. war plans for a potential conflict with China, a plan later walked back after press reports, and he visited the Pentagon for a private briefing on national security matters. When those plans leaked, he threatened legal action and called for the prosecution of Pentagon insiders. President Trump later acknowledged that Musk\'92s business ties to China made it inappropriate to share war plans with him, but the fact that such a briefing had been contemplated at all underscored how far private influence had penetrated the national security sphere.\
