Against this backdrop, foreign policy shifted in ways that favored authoritarian partners and weakened democratic alliances. The Pentagon froze intelligence and weapons packages to Ukraine, causing anxiety among Ukrainian forces and allies. The administration withdrew from an international body investigating responsibility for the invasion of Ukraine and terminated a contract with a university team that had been tracking Russian abductions of Ukrainian children for European law enforcement. President Trump held calls with Vladimir Putin about a possible ceasefire, during which Putin reportedly mocked him and demanded an end to U.S. military aid to Ukraine. At the same time, the administration considered relinquishing the U.S. role of Supreme Allied Commander Europe within NATO, a move that would reduce American influence in the alliance. Big technology companies, including Musk\'92s X, asked the administration to challenge Australian media laws they described as coercive, aligning U.S. trade pressure with corporate interests abroad. These choices signaled a reorientation of American power away from support for democratic partners and toward accommodation of strongmen and corporate demands.\
